From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Eugene <eugenebosyakov@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 03 May 2026 00:00:00 +0300
Subject: [PATCH] app/windows: stable PointerID for the mouse

The Windows backend reports two different PointerIDs for the same
physical mouse: scrollEvent omitted PointerID from its pointer.Event
so it defaulted to 0, while pointerUpdate forwarded whatever ID
Windows assigned via getPointerIDwParam (typically 1+). pointerQueue
keys state.pointers by PointerID, so a single mouse produced two
persistent entries — one for scroll, one for move/press/release.

The scroll-derived entry never received a Leave event (subsequent
moves went to the other entry's id) so its entered set never
emptied, the entry was never removed, and pointerQueue.Frame ran
hit-test for it every frame at the user's last scroll-wheel
position. Because state.cursor is threaded through every pointer
in pointerQueue.Frame's loop, the stale entry's hit-test
overwrote the live pointer's cursor resolution every frame:
hovering an anchor badge correctly resolved CursorPointer for the
live pointer, then the phantom (sitting over an unrelated editor
cell) overwrote it with CursorText for the same frame. The user
saw the wrong cursor and a hover that appeared "stuck" on multiple
rows simultaneously — both symptoms are the phantom pointer
carrying stale entered tags.

EnableMouseInPointer also reassigns the mouse's PointerID across
focus / window-leave events, which can compound the issue with
additional phantom entries; this fix subsumes that drift too by
keeping the ID Gio sees stable regardless of Windows-side renumbering.

Normalise all Source=Mouse events to a single stable PointerID at
the platform layer so pointerQueue sees one entry per physical
mouse. Touch events keep their Windows-assigned IDs because
multi-touch needs distinct pointers per finger. The stable ID is
^pointer.ID(0) so it cannot collide with Windows-assigned touch
finger IDs (which start at small values).

Signed-off-by: Eugene <eugenebosyakov@gmail.com>
---
 app/os_windows.go | 11 ++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/app/os_windows.go b/app/os_windows.go
--- a/app/os_windows.go
+++ b/app/os_windows.go
@@ -529,12 +529,19 @@ func (w *window) hitTest(x, y int) uintptr {
 	return windows.HTCLIENT
 }

+// mouseStablePID is the PointerID we report for every Source=Mouse event.
+// Windows assigns different IDs to a single physical mouse between
+// WM_MOUSEWHEEL (which previously emitted PointerID=0) and WM_POINTER*
+// events (where the ID comes from getPointerIDwParam), and EnableMouseInPointer
+// reassigns the mouse's ID across focus changes. Both paths produce phantom
+// entries in pointerQueue.state.pointers whose stale hit-tests overwrite the
+// live pointer's cursor resolution. Normalising to a single stable ID keeps
+// state.pointers to one Mouse entry. Chosen as max-uint so it cannot collide
+// with Windows-assigned touch finger IDs (which start at small values).
+var mouseStablePID = ^pointer.ID(0)
+
 func (w *window) pointerUpdate(pi windows.PointerInfo, pid pointer.ID, kind pointer.Kind, lParam uintptr) {
 	if !w.config.Focused {
 		windows.SetFocus(w.hwnd)
 	}

 	src := pointer.Touch
 	if pi.PointerType == windows.PT_MOUSE {
 		src = pointer.Mouse
+		pid = mouseStablePID
 	}

 	x, y := coordsFromlParam(lParam)
@@ -585,6 +592,7 @@ func (w *window) scrollEvent(wParam, lParam uintptr, horizontal bool, kmods key.
 	w.ProcessEvent(pointer.Event{
 		Kind:      pointer.Scroll,
 		Source:    pointer.Mouse,
+		PointerID: mouseStablePID,
 		Position:  p,
 		Buttons:   getPointerButtons(pi),
 		Scroll:    sp,
--
2.50.1.windows.1
